The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "green deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It has therefore become a benchmark for the world – a guide for the transformation toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, the first agenda, for everyone's use, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is a display of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy at first glance, a large number of subjects involved and related, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
Sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined based on objectives subject to a timeline, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (zero net emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, critics will view public consultation announcements as mere smoke and mirrors for dreamers.
But go tell the useless chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced over a year of protests turning into riots, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted in revolt this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately seeking how to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neoliberal adherents will once again mock and claim that the « market » will know how to remedy climate change.
But one only has to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, moving walkways, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that they cannot be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Every American election cycle now costs 8 billion dollars, if not more, and is funded by billionaires, by large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and by interest groups determined to lower taxes and at all costs protect the status quo.
The solutions offered by the market are a farce when politics is subjected to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows a government as it should be, and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not in a narrow party sense).
An mixed economy, which combines markets, regulatory power of the State, public sector and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies, which will allow the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and the collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, move toward a circular economy, and drastically reduce the use of primary resources.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Large oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensations, in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public aids.
The European plan rightly claims a 'just transition.'
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small share of its production, from 1 % to 2 %, towards the green economy, particularly in the areas of new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Financing will come from the private sector, as well as from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
The European Union accounts for approximately 9.1 % of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30 % and that of the United States 14 %.
Even if the European Union manages to fully implement its green deal, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the green deal.
Take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's top emitter of CO2 (although its per capita emissions remain half of those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, under pressure from the United States, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead offers China a positive, unambiguous partnership: working together to establish infrastructure, development, and sustainable technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen of Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
The EU has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
